    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Yordan Alvarez** (86.40) and **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (80.42) headlining our offensive strategy. **Yordan Alvarez** remains our premier offensive engine, buoyed by a significant +16% park factor and an elite xwOBA of 0.393 that positions him to dominate against Baz. Meanwhile, the aggressive pivot to **Pete Crow-Armstrong** is dictated by our heavy weighting toward stolen base potential; with an opponent offering a slow delivery and a high-yield matchup against the 5.19 xERA of Buehler, **Pete Crow-Armstrong** is primed to capitalize on base-path opportunities. **Trea Turner** (74.91) and **Kyle Schwarber** (73.00) also anchor the top of our lineup, with **Trea Turner** benefiting from a premium #1 slot against Mahle, despite the slight efficiency drag caused by the catcher's sub-2-second pop time.\n\nThe most difficult decision on today\u2019s card involved **Luke Raley** (43.58), whose marginal score narrowly edged out our bench options. While we looked closely at the potential utility of **Colt Keith**, the lack of a confirmed start forced his score to zero, effectively sidelining him in favor of **Luke Raley**'s guaranteed role in the lineup. Elsewhere, we continue to manage the roster health of **Christian Yelich** and **Lars Nootbaar**, both of whom remain on the IL, alongside **Zac Veen** who remains stashed in the minors. Investors should note that while **Dillon Dingler** (63.75) carries a strong projection due to the platoon advantage against the lefty P\u00e9rez, we are keeping a close watch on the game caps; with **Kazuma Okamoto** (59.88) and **Junior Caminero** (72.82) providing solid middle-infield consistency, we have sufficient depth to navigate any late-game adjustments should weather or defensive substitutions impact our secondary options like **Caleb Durbin**, **Hyeseong Kim**, **Carson Benge**, **Josh Smith**, **Chase Meidroth**, **Gary Sanchez**, **Jerar Encarnacion**, **Pedro Ramirez**, or **Luis Pena**.",
